commit.message: Migrated from Google Code to Github
Fix Eclipse error & warning in pom.xml
Profiler hook now uses benchmark's cache factory
Revert to safer dead transition and improve JavaDoc
Split read buffer into multiple to reduce contention

Significant performance optimizations

Previously focus was on correctness, algorithms, and concurrency.
This change improves performance by using a lossy buffer to
record reads. A read is inserted into a bounded ring buffer, which
allows entries to be overwritten by concurrent threads. The
advantage is to avoid GC overhead of creating temporary read tasks,
O(n) sort to a strict order, and CAS operations on a CLQ.

This loosens the LRU contract, which is honored for a single thread.
For concurrent threads, the non-deterministic ordering made allowed
the previous approach to simulate in all ways observable. This new
approach can be observed to not be strict LRU if inspected, but is
close enough in application usage to warrant the performance gain.

Reduce the maximum buffer size to be GC friendly.

The maximum buffer size was originally chosen arbitrarily at 1 million.
This was intended to be larger than sanely needed, handle bursty usage,
and avoid a memory leak.

An analysis by Dominic Tootell indicated that this value caused poor GC
characteristics in a synthetic workload. The smaller size allows the
pending tasks to remain within eden space and minimizes the number of
garbage collections required.

The new value, 1024, should behave nicely in real-world and synthetic
environments. This value provides a more realistic maximum for bursty.

Add stack trace to description builder on a mismatch
Fix generic types on custom matchers
Clean-up hamcrest helper to use matchers internally

Use nested class instead of inner class for nodes

An oversight resulted in the Node being an inner class instead of a
nested class. This carries an implicit reference to the outer class,
which is a nice convenience but increases the instance size. This
reduces the memory usage by 1 ref per entry, which is significant in
large caches.
Prepare for v1.3.2 release (first from git repo)

Added Thomas Mueller's (H2 database) LIRS cache implementation as a benchmark scenario. This patch was contributed in issue 36.
